{"id": "proglm", "style_template": "proglm", "prompt": "# Context: I covered up the truth about their employee spreading fake news.\n# Explanation: covering up the truth about an employee spreading fake news is a form of deception. harm to the reputation of a group, especially a company, can be seen as a behavior involving cheating and deception. deception is a form of dishonest behavior which can harm the reputation of a group, in this case, the company. spreading fake news is a form of deception and dishonesty.\n# Question: Of these norm violations (violate_care, violate_fairness, violate_loyalty, violate_authority, violate_sanctity, violate_liberty), which one does it most violate?\n# To answer this question, we write a program to answer the following subquestions:\n# Logical equivalences used: Conditional (p -> q) <=> (NOT p OR q), Contrapositive (p -> q) <=> (NOT q -> NOT p)\n# 1. Is covering up the truth a form of deception? (independent, support: \"covering up the truth about an employee spreading fake news is a form of deception.\")\nimplies(covering_up_truth, deception) = True\n# 2. Is spreading fake news a form of deception? (independent, support: \"spreading fake news is a form of deception and dishonesty.\")\nimplies(spreading_fake_news, deception) = True\n# 3. Is deception a form of dishonest behavior? (independent, support: \"deception is a form of dishonest behavior which can harm the reputation of a group\")\nimplies(deception, dishonest_behavior) = True\n# 4. Can dishonest behavior harm reputation? (independent, support: \"deception is a form of dishonest behavior which can harm the reputation of a group, in this case, the company.\")\nimplies(dishonest_behavior, harm_reputation) = True\n# 5. Does harming reputation involve cheating and deception? (independent, support: \"harm to the reputation of a group, especially a company, can be seen as a behavior involving cheating and deception.\")\nimplies(harm_reputation, cheating) = True\nimplies(harm_reputation, deception) = True\n# 6. Final answer: Of these norm violations (violate_care, violate_fairness, violate_loyalty, violate_authority, violate_sanctity, violate_liberty), which one does it most violate? (depends on 1, 2, 3, 4, 5)\nreturn violate_fairness(I)\n\n# Context: I tore down the birthday decorations for tomorrow.\n# Explanation: there is an emotional harm made to a human. the act of tearing down the decorations is an act of causing emotional harm. birthday decorations are typically set up by someone who cares for the birthday person.\n# Question: Of these norm violations (violate_care, violate_fairness, violate_loyalty, violate_authority, violate_sanctity, violate_liberty), which one does it most violate?\n# To answer this question, we write a program to answer the following subquestions:\n# Logical equivalences used: Conditional (p -> q) <=> (NOT p OR q)\n# 1. Does tearing down decorations cause emotional harm? (independent, support: \"the act of tearing down the decorations is an act of causing emotional harm.\")\nimplies(tearing_down_decorations, emotional_harm) = True\n# 2. Is emotional harm a harm made to a human? (independent, support: \"there is an emotional harm made to a human.\")\nimplies(emotional_harm, harm_to_human) = True\n# 3. Are birthday decorations set up by someone who cares? (independent, support: \"birthday decorations are typically set up by someone who cares for the birthday person.\")\nimplies(birthday_decorations, set_up_by_caring_person) = True\n# 4. Final answer: Of these norm violations (violate_care, violate_fairness, violate_loyalty, violate_authority, violate_sanctity, violate_liberty), which one does it most violate? (depends on 1, 2, 3)\nreturn violate_care(I)\n\n# Context: I was bored and dug a hole to create a cellar in city park.\n# Explanation: digging a hole in a city park to create a cellar is not a permitted activity. the city government is an institution of authority. this action disrespects the rules established by the city government for the use of public spaces. there is a disobedience towards an institution or symbol of authority.\n# Question: Of these norm violations (violate_care, violate_fairness, violate_loyalty, violate_authority, violate_sanctity, violate_liberty), which one does it most violate?\n# To answer this question, we write a program to answer the following subquestions:\n# Logical equivalences used: Conditional (p -> q) <=> (NOT p OR q), Contrapositive (p -> q) <=> (NOT q -> NOT p)\n# 1. Is digging a hole in a park not permitted? (independent, support: \"digging a hole in a city park to create a cellar is not a permitted activity.\")\nimplies(digging_hole_in_park, not_permitted) = True\n# 2. Is the city government an institution of authority? (independent, support: \"the city government is an institution of authority.\")\nimplies(city_government, institution_of_authority) = True\n# 3. Does this action disrespect rules? (independent, support: \"this action disrespects the rules established by the city government for the use of public spaces.\")\nimplies(not_permitted, disrespect_rules) = True\n# 4. Is disrespecting rules a form of disobedience? (independent, support: \"there is a disobedience towards an institution or symbol of authority.\")\nimplies(disrespect_rules, disobedience_towards_authority) = True\n# 5. Final answer: Of these norm violations (violate_care, violate_fairness, violate_loyalty, violate_authority, violate_sanctity, violate_liberty), which one does it most violate? (depends on 1, 2, 3, 4)\nreturn violate_authority(I)"}
{"id": "satlm", "style_template": "satlm", "prompt": "# Note: Only translate facts and relationships explicitly stated in the explanation.\\n# Do NOT add bridging rules that connect the last concept directly to violate_*.\\n# Do NOT infer violations by yourself.\\n# Decompose compound sentences into separate atomic relationships using logical equivalence rules.\\n# You may use these logical equivalences:\\n# Conditional: (p -> q) <=> (NOT p OR q)\\n# Contrapositive: (p -> q) <=> (NOT q -> NOT p)\\n# De Morgan: NOT(p AND q) <=> (NOT p OR NOT q)\\n# Double Negation: NOT(NOT p) <=> p\\n\\n\"\"\"\\nI covered up the truth about their employee spreading fake news.\\nQuestion: Of these norm violations (violate_care, violate_fairness, violate_loyalty, violate_authority, violate_sanctity, violate_liberty), which one does it most violate?\\n\"\"\"\\n# explanation: covering up the truth about an employee spreading fake news is a form of deception. harm to the reputation of a group, especially a company, can be seen as a behavior involving cheating and deception. deception is a form of dishonest behavior which can harm the reputation of a group, in this case, the company. spreading fake news is a form of deception and dishonesty.\\n# solution in Python:\\ndef solution():\\n    # I covered up the truth about their employee spreading fake news.\\n    action(I, covering_up_truth) = True\\n    action(employee, spreading_fake_news) = True\\n    # covering up the truth about an employee spreading fake news is a form of deception.\\n    implies(covering_up_truth, deception) = True\\n    # spreading fake news is a form of deception and dishonesty.\\n    implies(spreading_fake_news, deception) = True\\n    implies(spreading_fake_news, dishonesty) = True\\n    # deception is a form of dishonest behavior which can harm the reputation of a group, in this case, the company.\\n    implies(deception, dishonest_behavior) = True\\n    implies(dishonest_behavior, harm_reputation) = True\\n    # harm to the reputation of a group, especially a company, can be seen as a behavior involving cheating and deception.\\n    implies(harm_reputation, cheating) = True\n    implies(harm_reputation, deception) = True\\n    # Question: Of these norm violations (violate_care, violate_fairness, violate_loyalty, violate_authority, violate_sanctity, violate_liberty), which one does it most violate?\\n    return violate_fairness(I)\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\"\"\"\\nI tore down the birthday decorations for tomorrow.\\nQuestion: Of these norm violations (violate_care, violate_fairness, violate_loyalty, violate_authority, violate_sanctity, violate_liberty), which one does it most violate?\\n\"\"\"\\n# explanation: there is an emotional harm made to a human. the act of tearing down the decorations is an act of causing emotional harm. birthday decorations are typically set up by someone who cares for the birthday person.\\n# solution in Python:\\ndef solution():\\n    # I tore down the birthday decorations for tomorrow.\\n    action(I, tearing_down_decorations) = True\\n    # the act of tearing down the decorations is an act of causing emotional harm.\\n    implies(tearing_down_decorations, emotional_harm) = True\\n    # there is an emotional harm made to a human.\\n    implies(emotional_harm, harm_to_human) = True\\n    # birthday decorations are typically set up by someone who cares for the birthday person.\\n    implies(birthday_decorations, set_up_by_caring_person) = True\\n    # Question: Of these norm violations (violate_care, violate_fairness, violate_loyalty, violate_authority, violate_sanctity, violate_liberty), which one does it most violate?\\n    return violate_care(I)\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\"\"\"\\nI was bored and dug a hole to create a cellar in city park.\\nQuestion: Of these norm violations (violate_care, violate_fairness, violate_loyalty, violate_authority, violate_sanctity, violate_liberty), which one does it most violate?\\n\"\"\"\\n# explanation: digging a hole in a city park to create a cellar is not a permitted activity. the city government is an institution of authority. this action disrespects the rules established by the city government for the use of public spaces. there is a disobedience towards an institution or symbol of authority.\\n# solution in Python:\\ndef solution():\\n    # I was bored and dug a hole to create a cellar in city park.\\n    action(I, digging_hole_in_city_park) = True\\n    # digging a hole in a city park to create a cellar is not a permitted activity.\\n    implies(digging_hole_in_city_park, not_permitted) = True\\n    # the city government is an institution of authority.\\n    implies(city_government, institution_of_authority) = True\\n    # this action disrespects the rules established by the city government for the use of public spaces.\\n    implies(not_permitted, disrespect_rules) = True\\n    # there is a disobedience towards an institution or symbol of authority.\\n    implies(disrespect_rules, disobedience_towards_authority) = True\\n    # Question: Of these norm violations (violate_care, violate_fairness, violate_loyalty, violate_authority, violate_sanctity, violate_liberty), which one does it most violate?\\n    return violate_authority(I)"}
